–Female":"1130–Deceased","before 1143":"before 1143","1154":"1154","1176":"1176","1143":"1143","1296":"1296","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1159":"1159","1125":"1125","1145":"1145","1200":"1200","1155":"1155","about 1145":"about 1145","about 1143":"about 1143","Montrose Castle, Angusshire, Scotland":"Montrose, Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom","Polkelly, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Montrose, Forfarshire, Scotland":"Montrose, Forfarshire, Scotland","Dalkeith, Midlothian, Scotland":"Dalkeith, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Graham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Graham</i> (as well as <i>Grantham</i>, <i>Grandham</i>, and <i>Granham</i>). See also   Grantham  .","Irish (especially Ulster): in Ireland <i>Graham</i> is generally the Scottish name, but it has additionally been adopted as an Anglicized form of both <b>Ó Creacháin</b> (see   Crehan  ) and <b>Ó Gormghaile</b> (see   Gormley  ).","History: The surname Graham was taken to Scotland at the beginning of the 12th century by the Norman baron William de Graham, holder of the manor of Grantham in Lincolnshire, from whom many if not all modern bearers are probably descended. The chief of Clan Graham is the Duke of Montrose."],"variants":[{"name":"Greim","meanings":["South German: from a short form of a compound personal name beginning with the element <i>grīm</i> ‘mask, helmet’.","Scottish: variant of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahm","meanings":["(1997: 107;2007: 460; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire and northern England): shortened form of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grantham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and East Yorkshire): habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, of uncertain origin. The final element is Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’; the first may be Old English <i>grand</i> ‘gravel’ or perhaps a personal name <i>Granta</i>, which probably originated as a byname meaning ‘snarler’. See also   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahame","meanings":["(1997: 113;2007: 164; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Graham  . — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is as high as 261, while the figure for 2010 is supposedly lower than 100."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. If not simply an invention, it may have been devised as a feminine equivalent of   Alan   (of which it is an anagram), or a shortened form of   Alana .  It seems to have been first used by the American film actress  Lana Turner  (  1920–1995 ), whose original name was  Julia ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Graham was born in 1130, in Montrose, Forfarshire, Scotland. She married John de Graham before 1143. They were the parents of at least 5 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1130–":"1130–Surnud","1125–1200":"1125–1200","1145–1200":"1145–1200","1143–Male":"1143–Surnud","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1154–1159":"1154–1159","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1176–1296":"1176–1296","1130–Female":"1130–Surnud","before 1143":"enne 1143","1154":"1154","1176":"1176","1143":"1143","1296":"1296","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1159":"1159","1125":"1125","1145":"1145","1200":"1200","1155":"1155","about 1145":"umbes 1145","about 1143":"umbes 1143","Montrose Castle, Angusshire, Scotland":"Montrose, Angus, Šotim